Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: CMC Holdings, Safaricom Are Active

-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k
-- 
2011-03-15T14:32:11Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-15/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-cmc-holdings-safaricom-are-active.html
  Kenya ’s All-Share Index surged for
a third day, adding 1.7 percent to 73.95 by the 3 p.m. close in
Nairobi.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index dropped 1.2
percent to 25,125.42 by 2:35 p.m. in Lagos, a second day of
declines, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. Mauritius’s
SEMDEX Index retreated for a third day, losing 0.1 percent to
1,995.99 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis . The Ghana Stock
Exchange Composite Index increased 0.5 percent to 1,068.46 by
1:53 p.m. in Accra while Namibia’s FTSE  Namibia Overall Index (FTN098) 
retreated 1.6 percent to 838.21 by 3:53 p.m. in Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.    CMC Holdings Ltd. (CMCH)  , Kenya’s fourth-biggest car
dealership, fell for the first day in five, losing 20 cents, or
2 percent to 9.8 shillings. The company appointed Mary Ngige as
acting chief executive officer after Martin Forster left the
company as part of a “normal restructuring” exercise, she said.  “The aim of the board is to improve the performance of the
company and to grow it,” Ngige, currently group finance manager
at CMC, said in a phone interview today from Nairobi.    Safaricom Ltd. (SAFCOM)  , Kenya’s biggest mobile-network
operator, jumped to its highest level in more than two weeks,
climbing 15 cents, or 3.8 percent, to 4.10 shillings, as
Business Daily said the Communications Commission of Kenya’s
board recommended against renewing Director-General Charles Njoroge’s contract, citing people it didn’t identify.  “If you look at some of the challenges the sector has faced
it is partly because of the regulator,” Eric Musau, an analyst
at Nairobi-based African Alliance Securities Kenya Ltd., said in
a phone interview today. The commission cut the rate mobile-
phone operators charge each other to transmit calls across
networks by half, it said Aug. 19. The lowering prompted a
reduction in calling rates that could cost the four mobile-phone
companies as much as 26 billion shillings ($300.6 million) in
lost revenue this year, Safaricom Chief Executive Officer Bob Collymore said Jan. 20  To contact the reporter on this story:
